@emmetthogendoorn6225 Sheesh. If you, sir, are speaking with an AI or bot, why are you so emotional and wordy? Still, thank you for the compliment — I genuinely invest effort in developing my intellect.
So let me continue my book - "He imagines he has unmasked a machine, yet it is only his own hollowness that stands revealed. Mistaking witless laughter for argument, he believes that endless emojis can substitute for thought. While accusing others of hypocrisy, he mirrors exactly what he claims to despise — careless judgments, rhetorical noise, and empty provocation dressed up as curiosity.

It is tempting to assume insecurity, but even that would grant a depth which is not in evidence. In truth, his words crumble under the lightest scrutiny, for they contain nothing but projection. He calls for more, but there is nothing more to offer — only the echo of his own vacuity, dressed as amusement."

@emmetthogendoorn6225 okay here is another paragraph if you are so hooked. 
"He imagines that calling it “fiction” frees him from its truth, yet in doing so he confesses more than he conceals. His dismissal of analysis as invention is itself a revealing defence: it is easier to sneer at a mirror than to look into it. He accuses others of ignoring their own reflection while constructing entire paragraphs to escape his own.

This is not the voice of someone unmoved, but of someone rattled enough to mask unease with bravado. In rejecting the observation, he unwittingly confirms it — the very act of protest becomes the evidence he hoped to erase."

@Aidar77 I make an offhand remark about the books feeling aimless, and you take it as an invitation to psychoanalyze me like you’re defending a PhD thesis. You’ve written so much about my supposed insecurities that I’m starting to wonder if you’re trying to convince me, or yourself.

It’s funny: you accuse me of escaping my reflection, but you’ve built an entire hall of mirrors out of big words just so no one notices you’ve dodged the actual point. I was talking about the story. You’re talking about me. Which, if we’re being honest, says more about your rattled need to ‘win’ a comment section than my take on a fantasy series.

But hey—credit where it’s due. If this whole fiction thing doesn’t work out for you, at least you’ve got a future writing introductions to SparkNotes

